Abstract The γ-butyrolactone (GBL) autoregulator–receptor systems play a role in controlling secondary metabolism and/ or morphological differentiation in many Streptomyces spe- cies. We previously identified the aur1 gene cluster, located on the Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239 large linear plasmid pSA3239, which is responsible for the production of the angucycline antibiotic auricin. Here, we describe the characterisation of two genes, sagA and sagR, encoding GBL autoregulatory signalling homologues, which lie in the up- stream part of the aur1 cluster. SagA was similar to GBL synthases and SagR to GBL receptors. The expression of each gene is directed by its own promoter, sagAp for sagA and sagRp for sagR. Both genes were active mainly during the exponential phase, and their transcription was interdependent. The disruption of sagA abolished auricin production, while the disruption of sagR resulted in precocious but dramatically reduced auricin production. Transcription from the aur1Pp and aur1Rp promoters, which direct the expression of auricin-specific cluster-situated regulators (CSRs), was also precocious and increased in the sagR mutant strain. In addi- tion, SagR was also shown to specifically bind both promoters in vitro. These results indicated that the SagA–SagR GBL system regulates auricin production. Unlike many other GBL receptors, SagR does not bind its own promoter, but Aur1R, an auricin-specific repressor from the family of pseudo GBL receptors, does bind both sagAp and sagRp promoters. Keywords Antibiotics . Auricin . Gamma-butyrolactone . Polyketide . Regulation . Secondary metabolite . Streptomyces The Gram-positive, filamentous, soil-dwelling bacteria of the genus Streptomyces are characterised by a complex morpho- logical differentiation and by the ability to produce a wide variety of biologically active secondary metabolites, including the majority of known antibiotics. Secondary metabolite pro- duction is co-ordinated with morphological differentiation and often occurs in a growth phase-dependent manner, usually at the end of the exponential growth phase and is influenced by a variety of physiological and environmental factors. The bio- synthesis of secondary metabolites is also strictly regulated, involving at least two different levels of regulation: a lower, pathway-specific level using cluster-situated regulators (CSRs) and a higher one involving various global regulators with pleiotropic roles in stress response and morphological differentiation which affect antibiotic production only indi- rectly. Many of these pleiotropic regulatory genes influence activity of the CSR genes (Bibb 2005; Martin and Liras 2010; Liu et al. 2013). Among the global regulatory systems which influence secondary metabolism are those which make use of a γ- butyrolactone (GBL) autoregulator, a small diffusible signal- ling molecule. These GBL systems consist of a GBL synthase and a cognate GBL receptor. The GBL receptors belong to the TetR family and bind a specific DNA sequence (an

autoregulatory element or autoregulatory element (ARE)) up- stream of their target genes, thereby repressing their transcrip- tion usually during the exponential phase. Binding of the appropriate GBL autoregulator to the GBL receptor prevents this binding, allowing induction of transcription of the target gene to occur. In general, the target genes for GBL receptors are CSRs for secondary metabolites. Thus, GBLs regulate and co-ordinate secondary metabolite production. In some Streptomyces species, the GBL autoregulator-receptor signal- ling cascade also affects morphological differentiation (Takano 2006; Nishida et al. 2007). While GBL systems have been identified in numerous streptomycetes (Nishida et al. 2007), only four of them along with their associated GBL autoregulators have been characterised. They include the A- factor-AfsA–ArpA system of Streptomyces griseus (Horinouchi 2007), the SCB1-ScbA–ScbR system of Strepto- myces coelicolor (Takano et al. 2001), the IM-2-FarX–FarA system of Streptomyces lavendulae (Kitani et al. 2010) and the VB-BarX–BarA system of Streptomyces virginiae (Lee et al. 2010). Likewise, only a few reports have been published about the biosynthesis of GBLs; the S. griseus A-factor has probably been the most thoroughly studied. AfsA catalyses the condensation of dihydroxyacetone phosphate and a keto acid derivative to produce an A-factor intermediate, which is then modified by a phosphatase and a reductase to yield the final A-factor (Kato et al. 2007). Three additional representa- tives of the GBL synthase family, FarX of S. lavendulae, ScbA of S. coelicolor and BarX of S. virginiae, have also been shown to play a role in the biosynthesis of their respec- tive GBLs, IM-2, SCB1 and VB (Kitani et al. 2010; Hsiao et al. 2007; Lee et

BarX of S. virginiae, have also been shown to play a role in the biosynthesis of their respec- tive GBLs, IM-2, SCB1 and VB (Kitani et al. 2010; Hsiao et al. 2007; Lee et al. 2010); however, their precise biochem- ical functions are still unknown. Interestingly, two of these, BarX and ScbA, seem to have an additional regulatory func- tion (Kawachi et al. 2000; Takano et al. 2001).

We previously identified a type II polyketide synthase gene cluster, aur1, which is responsible for the production of the angucycline-like polyketide antibiotic auricin in Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239 (Novakova et al. 2002). Recently, we found that the cluster is not located in the chromosome of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239, but on pSA3239, a large linear plasmid (Novakova et al. 2013). Auricin is a unique angucycline polyketide conjugated to an amino deoxyhexose D-forosamine, and it is produced during a very narrow time period of several hours following entry into the stationary phase. This unusual phenomenon likely arises from the com- plex regulation of auricin biosynthesis, which involves several CSRs (Kutas et al. 2013; Kormanec et al. 2014). Four of them have already been characterised: Aur1P, an “atypical” re- sponse regulator that has been shown to specifically activate the expression of the auricin biosynthetic genes by directly binding and activating the aur1Ap promoter, triggering the expression of 22 structural genes (aur1A–aur1U) from the auricin cluster (Novakova et al. 2005). Aur1R has been shown

to repress the expression of the auricin-specific CSR gene aur1P gene by directly binding the aur1Pp promoter (Novakova et al. 2010). It belongs to a subfamily of pseudo GBL autoregulator receptors that do not appear to bind GBL autoregulators. They occupy an independent branch in the GBL autoregulator receptor phylogenetic tree (Nishida et al. 2007). The other two CSRs, Aur1PR3 and Aur1PR4, belong to the SARP family of transcriptional activators. They are also both involved in auricin regulation, most likely in the regula- tion of putative auricin tailoring biosynthetic genes. Interest- ingly, they are under the differential control of Aur1R and Aur1P (Novakova et al. 2011; Rehakova et al. 2013). Sequence analysis of the upstream region of the aur1 cluster revealed two genes, sagA and sagR, encoding proteins homologous to those of GBL regulatory systems (Novakova et al. 2013). The aim of the present study was to characterise their role in auricin production in S. aureofaciens CCM 3239. For this purpose, these genes were inactivated by gene re- placement, and auricin production was investigated in the resulting mutants. We provide evidence that sagA is essential for auricin production, and sagR is a negative regulator of auricin only during the early exponential phase. Gene expres- sion analysis by S1 nuclease mapping was used to characterise the expression of both genes and their interdependence. The results also show that SagR is a transcriptional repressor of both aur1P and aur1R genes. Finally, we showed that Aur1R directly binds both promoters for the GBL system, sagAp and sagRp, and that their expression was also deregulated in the aur1R mutant. Bacterial strains, plasmids and culture conditions

The S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 wild-type strain was from the Czechoslovak Collection of Microorganisms, Brno, Czech Republic. The S. aureofaciens Δaur1R mutant strain was described in Novakova et al. The Streptomyces integrative plasmid pPM927 (Smokvina et al. 1990) was used for the complemen- tation studies. Analysis of auricin production

Spores (5×108 c.f.u) from all S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 strains were inoculated into 50-ml Bennet medium in 250- ml Erlenmeyer flasks, and the cultures were grown on an orbital shaker at 270 rpm at 28 °C. Four-millilitre aliquots were taken from the cultures at various time points, and auricin was extracted by ethyl acetate and analysed by TLC and HPLC as described previously (Kutas et al. 2013). In brief, extracted samples of auricin were dissolved in 96 % (v/v) ethanol, and 1- and 10-μl aliquots were subjected to TLC analysis on silica gel 60F254 plates (Merck) with n-butanol saturated with water. Dried TLC plates were analysed by biochromatography with soft nutrient agar (Kieser et al. 2000) containing a fresh Bacillus subtilis culture. The plates were incubated for 16 h at 37 °C and visually screened for growth-inhibition zones. HPLC analysis of 20-μl samples was performed on an OmmiSpher 5 C18 column (5 μm, 250× 4.6 mm, Varian, Lake Forest, CA) using a Varian ProStar HPLC system with a ProStar 325 UV–VIS detector (Varian, Lake Forest, CA) with acetonitrile and 0.5 % (v/v) acetic acid in water as a mobile phase and dual detection at 254 and 450 nm. Elution was carried out with a linear gradient of acetonitrile from 20 to 100 % for 30 min at a flow rate of 1 ml min−1. Under these conditions, auricin exhibited a reten- tion time of 9.3 min. Characterisation of the GBL genes sagA and sagR in the plasmid pSA3239

Sequence analysis of the aur1 gene cluster upstream region (Novakova et al. 2013) revealed two genes, sagA and sagR, which are significantly similar to GBL autoregulatory signal- ling proteins (Fig. 1). A comparison of the deduced sagR protein product with sequence databases revealed a significant end-to-end similarity to members of the TetR family of bac- terial regulatory proteins; the highest similarity was to the GBL autoregulator receptor proteins from different Streptomyces species (Fig. S1). Like many other TetR- family regulators, SagR consists of a conserved N-terminal DNA-binding domain with a helix-turn-helix motif and a variable C-terminal effector binding domain (Cuthbertson and Nodwell 2013). A phylogenetic tree containing SagR and other GBL autoregulator receptors and pseudo GBL receptors from Streptomyces (Fig. S1) shows that SagR clearly belongs to the GBL receptor branch, and not the pseudo GBL receptor branch. In addition to their sequence differences, GBL receptors and pseudo receptors can also be distinguished by their pI values. GBL receptors are generally more acidic, and the pseudo GBL receptors are more basic (Choi et al. 2004). The pI values of SagR (5.1) and Aur1R (10.3) are consistent with their phylogenetic assignments.

The upstream region of sagR contains two genes, sa25 and sagA (Fig. 1). SagA, a 332 amino acid protein, exhibits high sequence homology to the AfsA family of GBL biosynthetic enzymes (Fig. S2). It is most similar to FarX (67 % identity, 80 % similarity), which is involved in IM-2 GBL biosynthesis in Streptomyces lavendulae FRI-5 (Kitani et al. 2010). Three additional representatives of this family, S. griseus AfsA, S. coelicolor ScbA and S. virginiae BarX, have also been shown to play a role in the biosynthesis of their respective GBLs, A-factor, SCB1 and VB (Kato et al. 2007; Hsiao et al. 2007; Lee et al. 2010).

The sa25 gene lies between the sagA and sagR genes and encodes a nucleotide-diphosphate-sugar epimerase homo- logue (Fig. S3). The highest similarity of sa25 was to S. coelicolor A3(2) SCO6267 (61 % identity and 71 % sim- ilarity), which encodes the GBL synthase ScbC and is located just downstream of the S. coelicolor A3(2) scbA gene (SCO6266) (D’Alia et al. 2011). BrpA, which is involved in butanolide reduction during the biosynthesis of S. griseus A- factor (Kato et al. 2007), is another close homologue. In addition, Sa25 was also significantly similar to three other nucleotide-diphosphate-sugar epimerase/dehydratases which, however, formed a separate branch of the phylogenetic tree (Fig. S3): S. virginiae BarS2, Streptomyces venezuelae JadW2 and Kitasatospora setae KsbS5. These three genes are also located in regions which flank the genes encoding GBL autoregulator–receptor systems (Aroonsri et al. 2012; Wang and Vining 2003), and BarS2 has also been shown to play a role in VB biosynthesis in S. virginiae (Lee et al. 2008). In sum, these sequence comparisons suggested that the sagA, sagR and sa25 genes from the pSA3239 large liner plasmid form a GBL autoregulator–receptor system. Disruption of sagA and sagR affects auricin production

To assess the role of the sagA and sagR genes in auricin regulation, the chromosomal copies of both genes were inactivated using a PCR targeting system for disruption of Streptomyces genes (Gust et al. 2003). The mutation of both genes did not affect growth and differentiation (data not shown), and the growth curves of both mutants were very similar to the S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 wild-type strain (Fig. 2a). The auricin production of both mutants was assessed as described previously (Novakova et al. 2010). Ethyl acetate extracts from the wild-type and the disrupted strains were prepared from liquid-grown strains cultivated in Bennet medium and analysed by TLC followed by a bioassay against B. subtilis. The deletion of sagA abolished auricin production (data not shown). Interestingly, the deletion of the sagR gene also negatively affected auricin production. Transcriptional analysis of the sagA and sagR genes

The expression of both sagA and sagR genes was investigated by S1 nuclease mapping using RNA isolated from wild-type S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 and the corresponding sagA and sagR mutant strains at various stages of growth in liquid Bennet medium. A single RNA-protected fragment was identified for both genes (Fig. 3) which corresponded to the sagAp and sagRp promoters. The TSP of sagAp was identified at a G 168 and of sagRp at an A 66 nucle- otides upstream of the most likely translation initiation codon (GTG) (Fig. 6e). No RNA-protected fragment was identified using a transfer RNA (tRNA) control (Fig. 3, lane C). As an internal check of RNA quality, S1 nuclease mappings were also performed using the same RNA samples but with a probe fragment specific for the hrdBp2 promoter, which is expressed fairly constantly during growth and differentiation (Kormanec and Farkasovsky 1993). RNA-protected fragments of similar intensities corresponding to the hrdBp2 promoter were identified in all RNA samples (Fig. 3c). Both promoters were mainly active during the exponential phase and were dependent upon each other: Transcription of either sagA or sagR was dramatically reduced when the other was disrupted. A similar transcriptional dependency was pre- viously observed for the homologous scbA–scbR GBL system in S. coelicolor A3(2), although in that system, expression was induced during the transition phase at the end of exponential growth (Takano et al. 2001). The sequences of both promoters and flanking regions are shown in Fig. 6e. The putative −10 and −35 regions of both promoters show rather high similarity to the consensus se- quence (TTGaCA-N16–18-TAgaaT) recognised by the major Streptomyces sigma factor σHrdB (Brown et al. 1992). Both regions are also separated by an optimal spacer of 16 bp (sagRp) or 17 bp (sagAp). Therefore, it is likely that both promoters are transcribed by an RNA polymerase holoen- zyme containing σHrdB.
Dependence of aur1P and aur1R transcription on sagR

GBL autoregulator receptor proteins usually regulate the ex- pression of the CSR genes of their respective antibiotic clus- ters. We previously characterised two critical auricin-specific CSRs, an atypical response regulator Aur1P (Novakova et al. 2005) and a TetR-family repressor Aur1R (Novakova et al. 2010). Interestingly, the activity of the promoters aur1Pp and aur1Rp, which direct the expression of both CSR genes, was induced at the same time point, after entry into the stationary phase (Novakova et al. 2005, 2010). Therefore, to investigate whether sagR disruption has an effect on the transcription of the aur1P and aur1R genes, S1 nuclease mapping was done using RNA isolated from the S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 wild- type and the sagR mutant strains cultivated in liquid Bennet medium. As shown in Fig. 4a, b, with the RNA isolated from the wild-type strain, single RNA-protected fragments were identified with TSPs that corresponded to the aur1Pp and aur1Rp promoters as published previously (Novakova et al. 2005, 2010). Both promoters were inactive in the exponential growth phase (7 and 9 h) and were induced at the beginning of the stationary phase (12 h) which is correlated with auricin production. However, when the RNA isolated from the sagR mutant is used, aur1Pp and aur1Rp also became active in the exponential phase, and the levels of their corresponding mes- senger RNAs (mRNAs) were reproducibly increased during the later time points. Microbial GBL autoregulators, such as the S. griseus A-factor, are small molecules which behave much like hormones. They play important roles in cellular communication in actinomy- cetes, controlling cell development and antibiotic production. They mediate this control by binding to GBL autoregulator receptors, thereby de-repressing the expression of genes which regulate antibiotic production or morphological differ- entiation (Takano 2006; Horinouchi 2007). In the present study, we characterised a GBL system from S. aureofaciens CCM 3239, whose genes sagA and sagR are located in the proximity of the auricin biosynthetic cluster aur1 on the large linear plasmid pSA3239 (Fig. 1). Sequence database searches revealed that SagA has high similarity to members of the AfsA family of GBL biosynthetic enzymes and SagR is similar to GBL autoregulator receptors (Fig. S1, Fig. S2). The results of all experiments reported in this study indicate that this GBL system regulates auricin production. As previously described, the aur1 auricin biosynthetic gene cluster in S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 is regulated by a com- plicated mechanism, which is responsible for the rather brief period of auricin production following entry into the station- ary phase (Kutas et al. 2013). Three positive auricin-specific CSRs have already been characterised. The atypical response regulator Aur1P and the SARP-family regulator Aur1PR3 are under the direct negative control of Au1R, a pseudo GBL autoregulator receptor from the TetR family. This arrangement ensures that the transcription of the auricin biosynthetic genes is correctly timed. A third positive regulator from the SARP family, Aur1PR4, has also been identified and is positively regulated by Aur1P (Kormanec et al. 2014).

A phenotypic analysis of the sagA and sagR mutants stud- ied here indicated that they are also involved in the regulation of auricin biosynthesis. Deletion of sagA abolished auricin production, while deletion of sagR resulted in a precocious, but dramatically reduced auricin production. Neither mutant affected morphological differentiation. This Sa- gA–SagR system is therefore similar to the FarA–FarX lavendulae (Kitani et al. 2010) and the system in S. BarA–BarX in S. virginiae (Lee et al. 2010), which also appear to influence only secondary metabolism and not morphological differentiation, and unlike the S. griseus AfsA–ArpA GBL system (Horinouchi 2007), which in- fluences both processes.

A transcriptional analysis of the CSR genes aur1P and aur1R in the sagR mutant indicated that SagR negatively regulates the expression of both these genes during the expo- nential phase. In the wild-type strain, the transcription of aur1P and aur1R is induced only after entry into the stationary phase. In the sagR mutant, on the other hand, they have become deregulated and are also active during the exponential phase (Fig. 4). The function of SagR as a repressor is consis- tent with the observation that sagR is predominantly expressed during the exponential phase in the wild-type strain (Fig. 3). EMSA and DNase I footprinting show that SagR directly binds both the aur1Pp and aur1Rp promoters on their putative −10 and −35 promoter regions (Fig. 5). This mode of binding makes SagR a transcriptional repressor, which is consistent with its putative function as a negative transcrip- tional regulator from the TetR family. Interestingly, in addition to the deregulation of both aur1Pp and aur1Rp promoters in the exponential phase, the levels of their corresponding mRNAs were also increased during the later time points, and this increase was much higher for the aur1Rp promoter. This may be caused by different binding affinities of SagR for these promoters. Detailed biochemical binding experiments (deter- mination of Kd values) would explain this phenotype. Such experiments are in progress. The SagR-binding sites on both promoters are identical to the Aur1R-binding sites previously mapped on these same promoters (Novakova et al. 2010). This may arise from the significant similarity exhibited by their N-terminal helix-turn- helix DNA-binding regions (Fig. S1). A similar case was recently reported for the BulR1 GBL receptor and GulR2 pseudo GBL receptor in Streptomyces tsukubaensis (Salehi- Najafabadi et al. 2014). The BulR1 and BulR2 both recognised identical sequences in six cognate binding regions in the bul regulatory region. It should be noted that the BulR1

and BulR2 operators, consisting of an inverted repeat of 24 bp, are highly similar to the Aur1R consensus sequence (Fig. 7). In most cases, GBL receptors directly repress the expres- sion of genes which positively regulate antibiotic production, and the disruption of these receptors results in increased secondary metabolite production (Takano 2006; Horinouchi 2007; Martin and Liras 2010). This was not the case for the sagR mutant, however, which exhibited a decrease in auricin production (Fig. 2). The most likely cause for this unusual phenotype is that SagR represses the expression of a positive regulator Aur1P and a negative regulator Aur1R. More spe- cifically, since Aur1R negatively regulates auricin biosynthe- sis by directly repressing aur1P, the much higher level of aur1R expression compared to that of aur1P after entry into the stationary phase in the sagR mutant (Fig. 4) inhibits more aur1P expression and, consequently, the expression of the auricin biosynthetic genes. This phenotype resembles that of two other GBL receptors, FarA of S. lavendulae (Kitani et al. 2001) and BarA in S. virginiae (Nakano et al. 2000). In both cases, the mutant of the corresponding gene resulted in an earlier but much reduced production of their respective sec- ondary metabolites, blue pigment and virginiamycin. These two systems might therefore be similarly regulated. The target for FarA is unknown. On the other hand, like the sagR–aur1R interaction, BarA represses the transcription of the barB gene, which encodes a pseudo GBL receptor (homologue of Aur1R) (Nakano et al. 2000), and BarB negatively regulates the tran- scription of the SARP-family virginiamycin-specific positive regulatory gene vmsR (Matsuno et al. 2004).

As noted, all experimental results indicate that SagR neg- atively regulates auricin production during the exponential phase in S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 by directly inhibiting the expression of aur1P and aur1R. Since SagR appears to be a GBL receptor, its repressor binding mode is likely re- lieved by binding a GBL autoregulator. Since the nearby gene sagA encodes a homologue of the AfsA family of GBL biosynthetic enzymes, it may be responsible for producing the autoregulator which relieves SagR. Generally, GBL recep- tors regulate their own production by binding their own pro- moters (Takano 2006; Horinouchi 2007); however, SagR seems not to do this. In several parallel EMSA experiments, we were able to detect SagR binding to the aur1Pp and aur1Rp promoters but could not detect its binding to its own promoter. This highly unusual situation is made even more surprising by the fact that the SagR promoter region also contains a sequence similar to the ARE consensus sequence of the Streptomyces GBL autoregulator receptors (Folcher et al. 2001) (Figs. 6 and 7). What was found, interestingly enough, is that pseudo GBL receptor Aur1R, one of the SagR targets, does bind the sagRp promoter in this ARE sequence (Fig. 6). These results were corroborated by a transcriptional analysis of sagA and sagR expression in an aur1R mutant: In both cases, transcription was deregulated and the genes became mainly active in the stationary phase rather than the exponential phase (Fig. 8). These results show that Aur1R is a negative regulator of both the sagAp and sagRp promoters during the stationary phase. In addition to regulating auricin biosynthesis, therefore, the lower-level CSR Aur1R also represses the expression of a higher-level regulator (GBL system) after entry into the sta- tionary phase, constituting a negative feedback loop. A similar feedback control was recently described for the homologous ScbA–ScbR–ScbR2 GBL system in S. coelicolor A3(2), where ScbA is a GBL biosynthetic enzyme, ScbR is a GBL receptor and ScbR2 is a pseudo GBL receptor homolo- gous to Aur1R. ScbR2 negatively controls the biosynthesis of the GBL SCB1 by directly repressing the transcription of scbA, which encodes the SCB1 biosynthetic enzyme. Like- wise, another pseudo GBL receptor, JadR2 in S. venezuelae, has also been shown to repress the transcription of jadW1, which encodes a putative GBL synthase (Wang et al. 2011). In contrast to the SagA–SagR–Aur1R system, however, ScbR2 does not bind the GBL receptor scbRp promoter, though the expression of scbR was still de-repressed in the scbR2 mutant. Interestingly, like SagR and Aur1R, ScbR and ScbR2 also both interact with the same ARE element in two different promoters. They interact with almost identical regions of the scbAp promoter in the scbA–scbR intergenic region, though only ScbR interacts with the divergent scbRp promoter (Takano et al. 2001; Wang et al. 2011). In addition, they interact with the same ARE element in the kasOp promoter, which directs the expression of the SARP-family positive regulator kasO (cpkO) of the cryptic type I polyketide biosynthetic gene cluster cpk in S. coelicolor (Takano et al. 2005). ScbR interacts with the kasOp promoter region in two positions, one at −3 to −35 and the other at −222 to −244 relative to the TSP of the promoter (Takano et al. 2005). The key positive CSR Aur1P directs the expression of the core auricin biosynthetic gene cluster from the aur1Ap promoter, which is induced at the onset of the stationary phase (12 h). In conclusion, we have identified the role of two genes, sagA and sagR, part of a GBL autoregulator–receptor system on the auricin production of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239. The GBL receptor protein SagR directly regulates the transcription of two auricin-specific CSR genes, aur1R and aur1P.
